---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { site } from "../data/site";

const effectiveDate = "June 2026";
---

<Base
  path="/privacy"
  title="Privacy — OurSay"
  description="How OurSay handles the limited information collected through the waitlist and contact forms on this site."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16 sm:py-24">
    <p class="mb-3 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-brand-600">
      Privacy
    </p>
    <h1 class="text-balance text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900">
      Privacy notice — this website
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-500">Effective {effectiveDate}</p>

    <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-slate-700">
      <p class="leading-relaxed">
        This notice covers only the OurSay marketing website at {site.domain} —
        specifically the waitlist and contact forms. It does not describe the
        OurSay platform itself, which will publish its own privacy and data
        practices before launch.
      </p>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">What we collect</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed">
          When you choose to join the waitlist or contact us, we collect only
          what you submit: your email address, an optional name, the type of
          participant you identify as (for example, constituent, representative,
          or journalist), and any optional message. We don't require anything
          else, and we don't track you to collect it.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Why we collect it</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed">
          To let you know when OurSay launches, to gauge interest across
          different audiences, and to respond to representatives and journalists
          who reach out. We use it for these purposes only. We do not sell it,
          and we do not use it for advertising.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Consent</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed">
          Submitting a form is voluntary and acts as your consent for us to
          contact you about OurSay. You can withdraw that consent at any time —
          every email we send will include a clear way to unsubscribe, and you
          can also email us directly to be removed.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Where the data goes</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed">
          For now, these forms are run through Google Forms, so submissions are
          processed and stored by Google under its own terms and privacy policy.
          We keep the information only as long as needed to contact you about the
          launch, and we'll migrate to our own infrastructure as the platform
          matures. We never commit this data to our public code repository.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Your rights</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed">
          You can ask us what we hold about you, ask us to correct it, or ask us
          to delete it. Under Alberta's Personal Information Protection Act (PIPA)
          and Canada's anti-spam legislation (CASL), you have the right to access
          your information and to withdraw consent to be contacted. To exercise
          any of these, email{" "}
          <a class="font-medium text-brand-700 hover:underline" href={`mailto:${site.contactEmail}`}>{site.contactEmail}</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Contact</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed">
          Questions about this notice? Reach us at{" "}
          <a class="font-medium text-brand-700 hover:underline" href={`mailto:${site.contactEmail}`}>{site.contactEmail}</a>.
          This notice may be updated as our practices evolve; the effective date
          above will change when it does.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
